We need to prove that:
$$ \int_{0}^{1} \left| \int_{0}^{t} g''(s) \, ds \right| \leq \int_{0}^{1} \int_{0}^{t} |g''(s)| \, ds $$
where $g''(s)$ is the second derivative of the function $g(s) = f((1-s)x + sy)$, and $f$ is a $C^2$ function.

This inequality is a direct consequence of the fact that for any integrable function $h(s)$, we have:
$$ \left| \int_{a}^{b} h(s) \, ds \right| \leq \int_{a}^{b} |h(s)| \, ds $$
This is because the absolute value of an integral is less than or equal to the integral of the absolute value. 

In our case, for each $t$, we have:
$$ \left| \int_{0}^{t} g''(s) \, ds \right| \leq \int_{0}^{t} |g''(s)| \, ds $$
