# Solving the Integral Inequality Problem in Lean 4

I'll solve the problem of proving the inequality involving integrals of derivatives. The goal is to show that:

$$ \int_{0}^{1} \left| \int_{0}^{t} g''(s) \, ds \right| \leq \int_{0}^{1} \int_{0}^{t} |g''(s)| \, ds \, dt $$

This inequality is a direct application of the fact that for any integrable function $h(s)$, we have $|\int_{a}^{b} h(s) \, ds| \leq \int_{a}^{b} |h(s)| \, ds$. 

In our case, for each $t$, we have $g'(t) - g'(0) = \int_{0}^{t} g''(s) \, ds$. Therefore, for each $t$, $|\int_{0}^{t} g''(s) \, ds| \leq \int_{0}^{t} |g''(s)| \, ds$. 

Integrating both sides from $0$ to $1$ with respect to $t$ preserves the inequality, giving us the desired result. 

